      <hedline>
        <hl1>Power Politics, and the Power of Thought</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jennifer Bird letter suggests that instead of Vice Pres Al Gore speaking more 'plainly' to get his ideas across, we should rise to intellectual challenge (Aug 7 James Atlas Op-Ed)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>To his credit, James Atlas (Op-Ed, Aug. 7) recognizes the tremendous value of having a president who thinks deep thoughts. I agree that it is exciting that at least one of our nation's potential new presidents is thinking long and hard about where our country is heading.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>To his credit, James Atlas (Op-Ed, Aug. 7) recognizes the tremendous value of having a president who thinks deep thoughts. I agree that it is exciting that at least one of our nation's potential new presidents is thinking long and hard about where our country is heading.</p>
        <p>But then Mr. Atlas suggests that Al Gore should speak ''plainly'' to get his ideas across. That reminds me of a third-grade teacher telling the class brain to speak less intelligently so that the other children will understand.</p>
        <p>Instead of asking the A student to dumb down, a good teacher would tell the other children to pay closer attention, assuming that they would rise to the challenge.</p>
        <p>Rather than speak more plainly, maybe Mr. Gore could raise the bar for all of us.</p>
        <p>JENNIFER BIRD  Washington, Aug. 8, 2000</p>
      </block>
